<TITLE> India urges regional fight against security threats </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 YEKATERINBURG, Russia, Tue Jun 16, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Prime Minister Manmohan Singh urged regional cooperation against terrorism and other security threats on Tuesday, shortly before he was due to meet Pakistani President Asif Ali Zardari. Singh made the call in a speech prepared for the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation summit of Central Asian states and neighbouring powers. "The spectre of terrorism, extremist ideologies and illicit drug trafficking haunts our region. Terrorist crimes committed today are transnational in nature," Singh said in the text of the speech, which was given to reporters. "It is imperative that we genuinely cooperate with one another and on a global scale to resolutely defeat international terrorism." Singh and Zardari were both in Yekaterinburg, the Russian city hosting the summit, a forum for Central Asian and neighbouring countries. India and Pakistan are both observer states in the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation. The two South Asian leaders are due to hold a rare bilateral meeting after the main summit -- their first meeting since ties went into deep freeze following attacks in Mumbai last November. New Delhi has put on hold a 5-year-old peace process, saying Pakistan must act decisively against the Lashkar-e-Taiba militants India holds responsible for the Mumbai attacks. Islamabad says it has detained some militants, but needs more evidence from New Delhi for further ac
